epatitis A virus","Hepatitis C virus","Hepatitis E virus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAmong the viral hepatitides, \u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C virus\u003C/strong\u003E has the highest rate of progression to chronic liver disease, with over 80% of infected individuals developing chronic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other viruses have lower rates of chronicity:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis D virus\u003C/strong\u003E requires concurrent Hepatitis B infection to replicate. While it can worsen liver damage, it is not independently the most likely to cause chronic infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus\u003C/strong\u003E becomes chronic in only about 5% of immunocompetent adults (though rates are higher in neonates and immunocompromised individuals)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A virus\u003C/strong\u003E causes acute self-limiting infection and does not progress to chronic disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis E virus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes acute self-limiting infection, though chronic infection can occasionally occur in immunocompromised patients\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high chronicity rate of Hepatitis C makes early detection and treatment crucial for preventing progression to cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis C virus infection progresses to chronic liver disease in over 80% of cases","Hepatitis A and E are typically self-limiting acute infections that rarely become chronic","Hepatitis B becomes chronic in approximately 5% of adult cases","Hepatitis D requires concurrent Hepatitis B infection and increases risk of chronic disease"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15417"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54794"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:57:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:59:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8108"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69341"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Rem